-- European shares extend winning run, boosted by German stocks
-- By Alistair Smout
-- Wed Apr 02, 2014 03:17AM EDT
-- None



LONDON, April 2 (Reuters) - European shares rose on Wednesday, gaining for their seventh session in the row, lifted by German stocks on optimism over the outlook for Deutsche Post <DPWGn.DE> and good U.S. sales figures for some car makers.

Deutsche Post, the world's biggest postal and logistics group, gained 2.5 percent, the top FTSEurofirst 300 <.FTEU3> riser in early deals, after unveiling its new medium-term financial targets, with traders saying targeted growth in earnings looked attractive. German stocks also benefitted from its heavy weighting in automakers, with BMW <BMWG.DE> and Porsche <PSHG_p.DE> up after strong U.S. car sales data. [ID:nL4N0MT3L2] The German DAX <.GDAXI> rose 0.3 percent, outstripping 0.1 percent rises for British <.FTSE> and French <.FCHI> blue chips.